description:
Mixophyes fleayi, commonly known as Fleay's barred frog, is a species of large frog endemic to the subtropical rainforests of southeast Queensland and northeast New South Wales in Australia. It belongs to the genus Mixophyes, which is a group of large, terrestrial frogs found in eastern Australia.

Fleay's barred frog is characterized by its large size, with adults typically reaching lengths of 70-100 mm. It has a robust, stocky build and a broad, flattened head. The dorsal (upper) surface of the frog is brown or olive-green, with distinct dark brown or black cross-bars or bands. The ventral (underside) surface is pale, often with a marbled or mottled pattern.

These frogs are nocturnal and primarily terrestrial, spending the majority of their time on the forest floor. They are known to be excellent jumpers and can leap distances of up to 2 meters. Fleay's barred frog is an opportunistic predator, feeding on a variety of invertebrates and small vertebrates.

The breeding biology of Mixophyes fleayi is not well-studied, but it is known to breed during the warmer months, with females laying their eggs in permanent or semi-permanent water bodies, such as streams and ponds. The tadpoles undergo a relatively long larval stage before metamorphosing into adult frogs.

Fleay's barred frog is considered a vulnerable species due to habitat loss and degradation caused by factors such as land clearing, urbanization, and climate change. Conservation efforts are ongoing to protect and manage the remaining populations of this unique amphibian species.
